  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several significant legal precedents related to money laundering cases:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major case establishing corporate criminal liability for Bank Secrecy Act violations\n- Set precedent for financial institutions' reporting requirements\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Highlighted international money laundering through complex banking networks\n- Led to increased international anti-money laundering cooperation\n\n3. United States v. Monroe Street Real Estate (2006)\n- Expanded understanding of money laundering to include real estate transactions\n- Demonstrated broad interpretation of money laundering statutes\n\n4. Republic of Philippines v. Marcos (1986)\n- Significant case addressing international money laundering by government officials\n- Established principles for asset recovery\n\n5. Sections of Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act\n- Provide legal framework for prosecuting money laundering\n- Define specific reporting and compliance requirements\n\nThese cases have shaped understanding of money laundering laws, reporting obligations, and prosecution strategies. Each established important legal principles regarding financial crimes and institutional responsibilities.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific cases or precedents?",
